\f0\b Introduction
\f1\b0 \
\
SilverService is an application that allows users to define System Services (i.e., those things that appear in "Services" under the application menu. based on Unix shell commands. These can take take input from the application via standard input or as an argument, and output can be displayed in a separate window, or returned to the calling application.\
\

\f0\b Installation
\f1\b0 \
\
First, copy SilverService.app into an Applications diretory, i.e., one of the following directories (or a subdirectory thereof):\
\
/Applications/\
~/Applications/\
/Network/Applications\
/System/Applications\
\
Your probably want either the first (available to everyone, but needs to be installed by an administrator) or the second (can be installed by any user, but only available to that user). The third allows networked users to access the application. You almost certainly don't want to use the fourth one. Note that SilverService will not function properly unless it is installed under one of those directories - you can't run it from the Desktop, for example.\
\
Once you've copied the application to an appropriate location, launch it. The first time a user launches it, SilverService creates the appropriate files for that user and opens the Preferences window, so you can start to add services.\
\

