\f1\fs24 \cf0 \
\
Each row of the table corresponds to a service. The 
\f2\i Service Name
\f1\i0  can be anything you want; this is what appears in the Services menu (which is always ordered alphabetically, by the way). The 
\f2\i Service Command
\f1\i0  field contains the command to run when the service is envoked. Both of these fields are normal text fields - double click on them to edit the values.\
\
The 
\f2\i Input
\f1\i0  field specifies the way in which the shell command will receive input from the calling application. 'None' means that no input is taken from the calling application, 'stdin' means that the selected text is piped in on standard input, and 'string' means that the text is substituted for the characters "%@" in the command, before it is executed (as in the "Evaluate Python" service in the screenshot). At present, SilverService shell services only accept text input.\
\
Similarly, the 
\f2\i Output
\f1\i0  field determines what SilverService does with the output of the shell command (on standard output). "None" means that no output is read from standard output. "Panel" means that the result will be displayed in a windows; the text is editable, and may be copied to other applications in the normal way. "Service" means that the text is used as the output of the service; this usually means that the text is inserted into the calling application, replacing any current selection.\
\

\f2\i Note: if you set Input to "none", Output must be "service"; otherwise, the service doesn't interact with the calling application at all, and consequently OS X doesn't include it in the Services menu.
