\f0\b Uninstalling Silver Service (or: What The Hell Are You Doing To My Home Directory)
\f1\b0 \
\
There is no uninstalled for SilverService, but it is pretty easy to remove by hand. The application itself can be removed in the normal way. The application will disappear from the Services menu at the next login. Individual users' services are stored in ~/Library/Services/SilverService.service/ - these are the only files created by SilverService.\
\
Why does the application create the files here, and not in the more usual Library/Preferences or Library/Application Support? It's for the same reason that the application must be placed in a bona fide Applications directory. 
\f2\i domain
\f1\i0 /Applications and 
\f2\i domain
\f1\i0 /Library/Services (for each of the four file system domains - see Apple's developer documentation) are the locations searched when Mac OS X is building the Services menu.\
\

\f0\b Known Bugs
\f1\b0 \
\
If SilverService.app is not running, it should start when one of its services is envoked. At present, this does not happen. This can be worked around by ensuring that SilverService is running whenever you want to use the services. If you use it often, you may wish to add it to Login Items (in System Preferences).\
